---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "Interactive Knife Cut Reference Guide",
  "description": "Visual guide to standard culinary cuts: brunoise, dice, julienne, batonnet, chiffonade. Dimensions and uses for professional cooking.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "28 Grams"
  },
  "mainEntity": {
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the dimensions of a classic brunoise cut?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A classic brunoise cut measures precisely 1/8 x 1/8 x 1/8 inches (3mm x 3mm x 3mm). It is typically created by cross-cutting a julienne."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between julienne and batonnet?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A julienne is a fine matchstick cut measuring 1/8 x 1/8 x 2 inches (3mm x 3mm x 50mm). A batonnet is a larger stick cut measuring 1/4 x 1/4 x 2 inches (6mm x 6mm x 50mm). Batonnet is the starting point for a small dice."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why is uniform cutting important in cooking?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Uniform cuts ensure even cooking. If pieces are different sizes, smaller pieces will overcook and turn to mush while larger pieces remain raw in the center."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
};

export const meta = {
  title: "Interactive Knife Cut Reference | 28 Grams",
  description: "Visual guide to standard culinary cuts: brunoise, dice, julienne, batonnet, chiffonade. Dimensions and uses for professional cooking.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="28grams"
  title="Interactive Knife Cut Reference | 28 Grams"
  description="Visual guide to standard culinary cuts: brunoise, dice, julienne, batonnet, chiffonade. Dimensions and uses for professional cooking."
  canonical="https://28grams.vip/knife-cut-reference"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Interactive Knife Cut Reference</h1>
      <p>The Geometry of Flavor: Standard Dimensions for Culinary Precision</p>
    </div>

    <div class="article-body">
      <p>Welcome to the 28 Grams visual guide for culinary cuts. Precision in cutting is not merely about aesthetics; it is the fundamental basis for controlling thermodynamics during cooking. Before diving into the specifics of dimensions, ensure your foundation is solid by reading our <a href="/knife-skills-guide">complete pillar guide to knife skills</a>. You can also explore our <a href="/vegetable-prep-times">prep times reference</a> and <a href="/knife-sharpening-guide">sharpening guide</a> to optimize your workflow further.</p>

      <h2>Select a Cut Type</h2>
      <p>Click on any of the standard cuts below to view exact dimensions, techniques, and typical culinary applications.</p>

      <div class="cut-grid">
        <button class="cut-btn active" data-target="brunoise">Brunoise</button>
        <button class="cut-btn" data-target="small-dice">Small Dice</button>
        <button class="cut-btn" data-target="medium-dice">Medium Dice</button>
        <button class="cut-btn" data-target="large-dice">Large Dice</button>
        <button class="cut-btn" data-target="julienne">Julienne</button>
        <button class="cut-btn" data-target="batonnet">Batonnet</button>
        <button class="cut-btn" data-target="chiffonade">Chiffonade</button>
        <button class="cut-btn" data-target="mince">Mince</button>
        <button class="cut-btn" data-target="rough-chop">Rough Chop</button>
      </div>

      <div class="cut-details-container">
        <!-- Brunoise -->
        <div class="card cut-card active" id="brunoise">
          <h3>Brunoise (Fine Dice)</h3>
          <div class="specs">
            <span class="spec-badge">Imperial: 1/8" x 1/8" x 1/8"</span>
            <span class="spec-badge">Metric: 3mm x 3mm x 3mm</span>
          </div>
          <p><strong>The Science:</strong> The brunoise provides maximum surface area relative to volume, allowing for rapid flavor extraction in liquids and practically melting into sauces.</p>
          <p><strong>Technique:</strong> Square off the vegetable. Cut 1/8-inch planks. Stack and cut into 1/8-inch matchsticks (julienne). Finally, cross-cut the matchsticks at 1/8-inch intervals.</p>
          <p><strong>Uses:</strong> Consommé garnishes, fine sauces, duxelles, delicate farces (stuffings).</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Small Dice -->
        <div class="card cut-card" id="small-dice">
          <h3>Small Dice (Macédoine - Fine)</h3>
          <div class="specs">
            <span class="spec-badge">Imperial: 1/4" x 1/4" x 1/4"</span>
            <span class="spec-badge">Metric: 6mm x 6mm x 6mm</span>
          </div>
          <p><strong>The Science:</strong> Small enough to cook quickly, but large enough to retain structural integrity and textural identity in a finished dish.</p>
          <p><strong>Technique:</strong> Square off. Cut 1/4-inch planks. Cut into 1/4-inch sticks (batonnet). Cross-cut at 1/4-inch intervals.</p>
          <p><strong>Uses:</strong> Soups, salsas, fine mirepoix for quick-cooking pan sauces.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Medium Dice -->
        <div class="card cut-card" id="medium-dice">
          <h3>Medium Dice (Macédoine - Standard)</h3>
          <div class="specs">
            <span class="spec-badge">Imperial: 1/2" x 1/2" x 1/2"</span>
            <span class="spec-badge">Metric: 12mm x 12mm x 12mm</span>
          </div>
          <p><strong>The Science:</strong> The perfect equilibrium for extended cooking. The surface caramelizes well, while the interior is protected from turning to mush over 30-45 minutes of simmering.</p>
          <p><strong>Technique:</strong> Square off. Cut 1/2-inch planks. Cut into 1/2-inch sticks. Cross-cut at 1/2-inch intervals.</p>
          <p><strong>Uses:</strong> Standard mirepoix for soups and braises, ratatouille, home fries.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Large Dice -->
        <div class="card cut-card" id="large-dice">
          <h3>Large Dice (Carré)</h3>
          <div class="specs">
            <span class="spec-badge">Imperial: 3/4" x 3/4" x 3/4"</span>
            <span class="spec-badge">Metric: 20mm x 20mm x 20mm</span>
          </div>
          <p><strong>The Science:</strong> Low surface-area-to-volume ratio protects the interior during prolonged heat exposure (1-3 hours).</p>
          <p><strong>Technique:</strong> Square off. Cut 3/4-inch planks. Cut into 3/4-inch sticks. Cross-cut at 3/4-inch intervals.</p>
          <p><strong>Uses:</strong> Long braises, stews (like Boeuf Bourguignon), roasted root vegetables, stocks (mirepoix).</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Julienne -->
        <div class="card cut-card" id="julienne">
          <h3>Julienne (Allumette / Matchstick)</h3>
          <div class="specs">
            <span class="spec-badge">Imperial: 1/8" x 1/8" x 2"</span>
            <span class="spec-badge">Metric: 3mm x 3mm x 50mm</span>
          </div>
          <p><strong>The Science:</strong> Rapid heat transfer due to extreme thinness. Allows firm vegetables to become pliable quickly when stir-fried or blanched.</p>
          <p><strong>Technique:</strong> Square off. Cut 2-inch long sections. Slice into 1/8-inch planks. Stack and slice lengthwise at 1/8-inch intervals.</p>
          <p><strong>Uses:</strong> Stir-fries, slaws, raw garnishes, spring rolls.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Batonnet -->
        <div class="card cut-card" id="batonnet">
          <h3>Batonnet (Small Stick)</h3>
          <div class="specs">
            <span class="spec-badge">Imperial: 1/4" x 1/4" x 2"</span>
            <span class="spec-badge">Metric: 6mm x 6mm x 50mm</span>
          </div>
          <p><strong>The Science:</strong> Provides structural crunch while being small enough for comfortable bites. The foundational cut for the small dice.</p>
          <p><strong>Technique:</strong> Square off. Cut 2-inch long sections. Slice into 1/4-inch planks. Stack and slice lengthwise at 1/4-inch intervals.</p>
          <p><strong>Uses:</strong> French fries (allumette style), vegetable crudité platters, stir-fries.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Chiffonade -->
        <div class="card cut-card" id="chiffonade">
          <h3>Chiffonade (Ribbons)</h3>
          <div class="specs">
            <span class="spec-badge">Width: 1/16" to 1/8"</span>
            <span class="spec-badge">Width: 1mm to 3mm</span>
          </div>
          <p><strong>The Science:</strong> Rolling minimizes cellular damage and oxidation (browning) by exposing less surface area to the blade and air than a rough chop. Preserves volatile aromatic oils in herbs.</p>
          <p><strong>Technique:</strong> Stack broad leaves (basil, sage, spinach) flat. Roll them tightly into a cylinder. Slice cleanly across the cylinder to create thin ribbons.</p>
          <p><strong>Uses:</strong> Herb garnishes, delicate leafy greens for fast wilting.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Mince -->
        <div class="card cut-card" id="mince">
          <h3>Mince (Hacher)</h3>
          <div class="specs">
            <span class="spec-badge">Size: < 1/16"</span>
            <span class="spec-badge">Size: < 1.5mm</span>
          </div>
          <p><strong>The Science:</strong> Complete cellular destruction. Maximizes the release of allicin in garlic or volatile oils in herbs, resulting in the most pungent and intense flavor profile possible.</p>
          <p><strong>Technique:</strong> No precise geometric rules. Use a rapid rocking motion with the chef's knife, keeping the tip anchored and moving the heel over the ingredient until it forms a paste-like consistency.</p>
          <p><strong>Uses:</strong> Garlic, ginger, shallots for marinades and vinaigrettes where you want flavor without texture.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Rough Chop -->
        <div class="card cut-card" id="rough-chop">
          <h3>Rough Chop</h3>
          <div class="specs">
            <span class="spec-badge">Size: Variable</span>
            <span class="spec-badge">Size: Approx. 3/4" to 1"</span>
          </div>
          <p><strong>The Science:</strong> Used when structural integrity and uniform heat transfer are not critical to the final product, primarily because the ingredient will be discarded or pureed later.</p>
          <p><strong>Technique:</strong> Cut into relatively uniform pieces, but without the precision of squaring off edges. Speed is prioritized over geometry.</p>
          <p><strong>Uses:</strong> Mirepoix for stocks (to be strained), vegetables for roasting before pureeing into soup.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
      const buttons = document.querySelectorAll('.cut-btn');
      const cards = document.querySelectorAll('.cut-card');

      buttons.forEach(btn => {
        btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
          // Remove active class from all
          buttons.forEach(b => b.classList.remove('active'));
          cards.forEach(c => c.classList.remove('active'));

          // Add active class to clicked button and target card
          btn.classList.add('active');
          const targetId = btn.getAttribute('data-target');
          document.getElementById(targetId).classList.add('active');
        });
      });
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; color: var(--text-primary); line-height: 1.7; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.2rem; }

    .article-body h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--accent-color); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .article-body p { margin-bottom: 1.2rem; font-size: 1.05rem; }
    .article-body a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 4px; }

    .cut-grid { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 10px; margin-bottom: 2rem; justify-content: center; }
    .cut-btn { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.8rem 1.2rem; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 600; font-size: 1rem; transition: all 0.2s; }
    .cut-btn:hover { border-color: var(--accent-color); color: var(--accent-color); }
    .cut-btn.active { background: var(--accent-color); color: #fff; border-color: var(--accent-color); }

    .cut-details-container { min-height: 300px; }
    .cut-card { display: none; background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.1); }
    .cut-card.active { display: block; animation: fadeIn 0.3s ease-in-out; }
    .cut-card h3 { margin-top: 0; color: var(--accent-color); font-size: 1.8rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }

    .specs { display: flex; gap: 15px; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .spec-badge { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 15%, transparent); color: var(--accent-color); padding: 5px 12px; border-radius: 20px; font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.9rem; border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 30%, transparent); }

    @keyframes fadeIn {
      from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(10px); }
      to { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
    }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
